On Wed, 10 Jul 2002, David Schwarze wrote:

> At 10:22 AM 7/9/2002, westydriver wrote:
> >Saw that pulley.  Intrigued me as to why would that be better than the
> >other way.  then i for some reason flashed back to physics and remembered
> >that the larger pulley on the primary will increase the rate of turn of
> >the secondary but with less power needed at the primary than if you shrank
> >the secondary to do the same result.
>
> Nope - that would violate conservation of energy.  Can't get something for
> nothing.

I think the statement was imprecise.  enlarging the input pulley would
make the pulley system more efficient (less flexing losses) than shrinking
the output pulley.  You would still need more power to run the fan, but it
would be transmitted a bit more efficiently.

George Lyle

